Many hospitals, including the Ohio State University Medical Center, will take pictures of the blood vessels in a patient's abdomen before they decide to perform a breast reconstruction using the patient's own tissue.

 These pictures are called computed tomography (CT) angiograms and are like a map of each patient's anatomy.

 However, no study has been reported that determined how accurate these pictures are at showing the surgeon where all of the blood vessels were located.

